Report Accuracy, F1 and AUC¶

In [5]:
def report_metrics(model, X_test, y_test):
    # Compute metrics
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])
    
    metrics = ['Accuracy', 'F1 Score', 'AUC']
    values = [accuracy, f1, auc]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    bars = plt.bar(metrics, values, color=['#4CAF50', '#2196F3', '#FF9800'], edgecolor='black')
    
    for bar in bars:
        yval = bar.get_height()
        plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval + 0.02, f'{yval:.3f}', 
                 ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10)
    
    plt.title('Model Performance Metrics', fontsize=14, pad=15)
    plt.ylabel('Score', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylim(0, 1.1)  # Extend y-axis for label visibility
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=10)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
 

report_metrics(model, X_test, y_test)

Models should be presented with all visualizations to facilitate interpretation.¶

In [6]:
def visualize_model(model, X_test, y_test, feature_names):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))

    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    coef = model.coef_[0]
    indices = np.argsort(np.abs(coef))[::-1]
    plt.bar(range(len(coef)), coef[indices], color='#FF6347', edgecolor='black')
    plt.xticks(range(len(coef)), [feature_names[i] for i in indices], rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.title('Feature Coefficients')
    plt.ylabel('Coefficient Value')
    plt.tight_layout()

    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xticks([0.5, 1.5], ['Unacceptable', 'Good'])
    plt.yticks([0.5, 1.5], ['Unacceptable', 'Good'])

    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    y_score = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_score)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='#4682B4', label=f'AUC = {roc_auc:.3f}')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='gray', linestyle='--')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

visualize_model(model, X_test, y_test, X_test.columns)

A brief summary taking into account the conclusions of the following analyses¶

The model highlights safety as the most important feature with a strong positive coefficient (~4), which means that higher safety ratings significantly increase the likelihood of a car being evaluated as "Good." capacity and buying_price also have notable positive impacts (~3 and ~1.5, respectively), suggesting that larger capacity and higher buying price (possibly reflecting quality) favor a "Good" evaluation. Conversely, maintenance_price, boot_size, and number_of_doors have negative coefficients (~-1.5, ~-1, and ~-0.5), implying that higher maintenance costs, larger boot sizes, or more doors slightly decrease the likelihood of a "Good" rating, though their impact is less pronounced.

The ROC curve shows strong discriminative ability with an AUC of 0.929, indicating the model effectively separates "Good" and "Unacceptable" classes. An AUC close to 1 (0.929) suggests high reliability in ranking predictions, making the model robust for decision-making in this context.

Depending on the DA goal, we could focus on increasing recall or precision

def plot_prediction(model, datapoint, feature_names, X_train):
    coef = model.coef_[0]
    intercept = model.intercept_[0]
    x = datapoint
    
    score = np.dot(coef, x) + intercept
    prob = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-score))
    pred = 1 if prob > 0.5 else 0
    class_label = 'Good' if pred == 1 else 'Unacceptable'

    explainer = shap.Explainer(model, X_train)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    plt.bar(feature_names, x, color='#FFB6C1', edgecolor='black')
    plt.title('Attribute Values')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    z = np.linspace(-5, 5, 100)
    sigmoid = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-z))
    plt.plot(z, sigmoid, color='#4682B4')
    plt.axhline(y=0.5, color='gray', linestyle='--')
    plt.axvline(x=score, color='red', linestyle='--')
    plt.plot(score, prob, 'ro', markersize=8)
    plt.title('Sigmoid Function')
    plt.xlabel('Logits (z)')
    plt.ylabel('Probability')
    plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

   
    
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    plt.text(0.5, 0.7, f'Logits: {score:.3f}', transform=plt.gca().transAxes, ha='center', bbox=dict(facecolor='lightblue', alpha=0.8))
    plt.text(0.5, 0.5, f'Probability: {prob:.3f}', transform=plt.gca().transAxes, ha='center', bbox=dict(facecolor='lightgreen', alpha=0.8))
    plt.text(0.5, 0.3, f'Predicted Class: {class_label}', transform=plt.gca().transAxes, ha='center', bbox=dict(facecolor='lightyellow', alpha=0.8))
    plt.title('Prediction Details')
    plt.axis('off')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    shap.waterfall_plot(explainer(x.to_frame().T)[0])
    plt.show()

def plot_probability_change(model, datapoint, feature_names, feature_idx):
    coef = model.coef_[0]
    intercept = model.intercept_[0]
    x = datapoint.values
    feature_name = feature_names[feature_idx]
    original_value = x[feature_idx]
    
    x_range = np.linspace(original_value - 5, original_value + 5, 200)
    probs = []
    
    for val in x_range:
        x_varied = x.copy()
        x_varied[feature_idx] = val
        score = np.dot(coef, x_varied) + intercept
        prob = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-score))
        probs.append(prob)
    
    threshold_idx = np.argmin(np.abs(np.array(probs) - 0.5))
    threshold_value = x_range[threshold_idx]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(x_range, probs, color='#4682B4', label='Probability')
    plt.axvline(x=original_value, color='green', linestyle='--', label=f'Original {feature_name} = {original_value:.2f}')
    plt.axvline(x=threshold_value, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Threshold {feature_name} = {threshold_value:.2f}')
    plt.annotate(f'Distance: {abs(threshold_value - original_value):.2f}', 
                 xy=((original_value + threshold_value)/2, 0.5), 
                 xytext=((original_value + threshold_value)/2, 0.6),
                 ha='center', va='bottom', color='black')
    plt.title(f'Probability vs {feature_name}')
    plt.xlabel(f'{feature_name} Value')
    plt.ylabel('Probability')
    plt.ylim(0, 1)
    plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

1. Try to answer this question in an analytical way based only on the values of the model parameters and explain why such a change is minimal (without sampling).¶

The Logistic Regression assign class acceptable for an alternative $\textbf{x}$ if $\sigma (\textbf w \textbf x^T + b) > 0.5$

From the visualisation we see that the safety column has the highest coefficient, and because the weights in Logistic Regression are independent (their influence is independent on other weights) the smallest possible change to change the classification is to change the safety attribute

Let's assume $x$ achieved logits $z$

To change its class we have define new attribute vector $x^\star$ where we decrease $x_\text{safety}$ by at least $\Delta x_\text{safety}$ where $z = 0$

$$ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \sigma(\textbf w^T \textbf x^\star + b) &= \frac 1 2 \\ \textbf w^T \textbf x^\star + b &= 0 \\ \textbf w^T (\textbf x - \Delta \textbf x) &= -b \\ z - \textbf w^T\Delta \textbf x &= -b \\ -w_\text{safety}\Delta x_\text{safety} &= -b-z\\ \Delta x_\text{safety} &= \frac {b+z} {w_\text{safety}}\\ \end{aligned} \end{equation} $$

To keep in mind is, is that we cannot e.g. lower safety to outside of it domain (it has to be at least 0)

Explain the predictions for these objects using at least one technique (Anchors LIME, SHAP, ... )¶

From the SHAP waterflow plot (displayed above) we can conclude the following:

The expected logits are -1.62 what means that on average the cars are "Unacceptable", and the values have to increase this likelihood to make car "Good"

For this instance:

  1. capacity = 1: +2.13. This is the largest contribution, indicating that a capacity of 1 significantly increases the likelihood of a "Good" rating. This aligns with the high coefficient for capacity (~3) from earlier visualizations.

  2. buying_price = 0: +1.01. A buying price of 0 also boosts the logit, reflecting that lower prices are associated with better evaluations in this dataset.

  3. boot_size = 1: +0.72 . A boot size of 1 adds to the positive prediction, consistent with a moderate coefficient

  4. maintenance_price = 0.667: -0.37. A maintenance price of 0.667 slightly decreases the logit, suggesting higher maintenance costs reduce the "Good" likelihood.

  5. safety = 0.5: -0.18. A safety rating of 0.5 has a small negative impact, despite safety having a large positive coefficient (~4) in earlier plots, possibly due to its low value

  6. number_of_doors = 0.667: +0.08. A moderate number of door has a minor positive effect.

Based on the parameters obtained, can we say something about the user’s preferences?¶

Yes, users likely prefer:

  1. High capacity (+3 coefficient, +2.13 SHAP)
  2. Low buying price (+1.5 coefficient, +1.01 SHAP)
  3. Moderate boot size (+0.72 SHAP).
  4. Low maintenance costs (-1.5 coefficient, -0.37 SHAP).
  5. High safety (+4 coefficient, but -0.18 SHAP at 0.5).
  6. Neutral on number of doors (-0.5 coefficient, +0.08 SHAP).

What was the influence of the criteria? Are there any criteria that have no effect, or have a decisive influence?¶

  1. Decisive Influence: capacity and safety.
  2. Moderate Influence: boot_size, maintenance_price and buying_price
  3. Minimal/No Effect: number_of_doors

Are there any dependencies between the criteria?¶

The underlying assumptions of Logistic Regression model is that the features are independent. We could do some feature engineering to tackle this (e.g. adding polynomial combinations) but in the current implementation we cannot examine the depedence (directly from the model), at least in an easy straightforward way.

What is the nature of the criterion, gain, cost, non-monotonic?¶

Reading from weights:

  1. Gain: capacity, boot_size, safety, number_of_doors
  2. Cost: buying price, maintanance_price
  3. Non-monotonic: Linear Regression cannot directly model nonmonotonic criterions

def plot_partial_dependence(model, X_train, feature_names):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
    for i in range(len(feature_names)):
        ax = plt.subplot(2, 3, i+1)
        disp = PartialDependenceDisplay.from_estimator(model, X_train, [i], feature_names=feature_names, ax=ax)
        disp.axes_[0].item().set_ylim(0, 0.6)
        plt.title(feature_names[i])
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

feature_names = ['buying_price', 'maintenance_price', 'number_of_doors', 'capacity', 'boot_size', 'safety']
plot_partial_dependence(model, X_train, X_train.columns)

The partial dependency graphs are consistent with our previous answers (e.g. strong upward safety and capacity influence, small influecne of number_of_doors) and comply with the simplicity of the model (monotonicity and no rapid changes)
